 </title><link>https://faq.i3wm.org/question/7560/is-i3-a-non-reparenting-wm/?answer=7562#post-id-7562</link><description>i3 is a reparenting window manager. However, it does have the oddity (as of 4.11, I am in the process of hopefully changing this) that window decorations are not drawn on the window's frame, but on the window's parent container's frame.</description><pubDate>Fri, 04 Dec 2015 14:15:06 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://faq.i3wm.org/question/7560/is-i3-a-non-reparenting-wm/?answer=7562#post-id-7562</guid></item><item><title>Comment by Airblader for &lt;p&gt;i3 is a reparenting window manager. However, it does have the oddity (as of 4.11, I am in the process of hopefully changing this) that window decorations are not drawn on the window's frame, but on the window's parent container's frame.&lt;/p&gt;
</title><link>https://faq.i3wm.org/question/7560/is-i3-a-non-reparenting-wm/?comment=7565#comment-7565</link><description>You shouldn't have to, no. I'm not setting it either and I do use Java applications :)</description><pubDate>Fri, 04 Dec 2015 16:30:58 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://faq.i3wm.org/question/7560/is-i3-a-non-reparenting-wm/?comment=7565#comment-7565</guid></item><item><title>Comment by zyguan for &lt;p&gt;i3 is a reparenting window manager. However, it does have the oddity (as of 4.11, I am in the process of hopefully changing this) that window decorations are not drawn on the window's frame, but on the window's parent container's frame.&lt;/p&gt;
